      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "source": [
        "As we can see the accuracies didn't change here, but we will generally compare these strategies:\n",
        "\n",
        "Missing data imputation replaces missing values with estimated values to make datasets suitable for analysis and machine learning.\n",
        "\n",
        "| Imputation Method | How It Works | Advantages | Disadvantages | Best Use Cases |\n",
        "|------------------|--------------|------------|---------------|----------------|\n",
        "| **Mean Imputation** | Replaces missing values with the average value of the feature. | Very simple, fast, easy to implement, works well for normally distributed numerical data. | Sensitive to outliers, reduces variance, ignores relationships between features. | Small amounts of missing data with normally distributed numerical features. |\n",
        "| **Median Imputation** | Replaces missing values with the middle value of the feature. | Robust to outliers, works well with skewed distributions, simple and efficient. | Does not capture relationships between variables, may reduce variability. | Numerical data with outliers or non-normal distributions. |\n",
        "| **KNN Imputation** | Estimates missing values using values from the most similar observations (nearest neighbors). | Preserves relationships between features, captures local data patterns, often more accurate than simple methods. | Computationally expensive, requires feature scaling, sensitive to the choice of `k`. | Medium-sized datasets with correlated features and meaningful similarities between samples. |\n",
        "| **Iterative Imputation** | Predicts missing values by modeling each feature using other features repeatedly until estimates stabilize. | Captures complex relationships, usually provides high accuracy, works well with correlated variables. | Slower, more complex, requires model assumptions, may overfit small datasets. | Large datasets where accuracy is important and features are strongly related. |\n",
        "\n"
